data.title: Loss of environmental data to DUKC system prior to a heavily laden ship departing Berth 7
data.description:
The port suffered a network outage as a result of the Geraldton Data Centre shutting down our servers. This caused a loss of environmental data to the DUKC system. This system crash was in the hours leading up to a heavily laden ship scheduled to depart Berth 7. Steve Pratt worked with Grant Ryan (Tremafon) and Meg Batchelor (OMC) and they were able to rectify the system just in time, which allowed the ship to depart with a known amount of available under keel clearance.
This is a single point failure which can have severe consequences. Without the DUKC system underkeel clearance is calculated via static tables, which are very conservative. For example, if a ship is given a draft to load up to using DUKC and in the period of time it takes the ship to achieve this draft the DUKC system stops working, there is the possibility that the ship would then not be able to depart using static tables for x amount of days/weeks until the environmental conditions are such to allow it to happen.
data.unplannedEvent: The port suffered a network outage as a result of the Geraldton Data Centre shutting down our servers. This caused a loss of environmental data to the DUKC system.
data.immediateActionTaken: Steve Pratt worked with Grant Ryan (Tremafon) and Meg Batchelor (OMC) and they were able to rectify the system

data.title: BWM 13/11/17 at 11:40am - DR841 damage to ladder when raising mast
data.description: A CMW operated DR841 at Ramp 38N and whilst tramming to the Southern end of the drill pattern, the mast access ladder fell out of its stowing position. When the mast was raised it made contact with the ladder, resulting in structural damage to the ladder. No injuries were sustained.
data.unplannedEvent: Ladder fell out of stowing position and got damaged when raising the mast
data.immediateActionTaken: CMW reported the incident to the supervisor D&A conducted – confirmed non-contributing Incident area secured, Investigation commenced Drill returned to work however must be repaired within 24 hours

data.title: S-I17030 - RR24MT2A Fire at Wallerawang
data.description: S-I17030 - RR24MT2A Fire at Wallerawang As part of planned rail track maintenance work for CRN, Speno Rail Grinder RR24MT2A was carrying out rail reprofiling tasks on the Up Main West Line at 165.600 Wallerawang Locality. As part of rail reprofiling process Speno undertook standard protocol mop up activities after grinding activities had been completed, with Speno returning to the grind site to monitor the grind area in case of any fire lighting from spot fires during grinding. The area was monitored for approximately 40 mins with no issues, and was subsequently wet down prior to vacating. After vacating the grind site it was reported to NSW Fire that a slow moving fire had started at the top of an embankment at the grind site at approximately 14:30 and slowly travelled down and along the slope within the rail corridor, with the RFS attending the site and extinguishing the area of approximately 50 Metres along the embankment length at 15:30. Rail operations were not impacted or endangered by this event. No damage to rail infrastructure occurred or were endangered as part of this event. No people were considered at risk as part of this event. This fire did not escape the corridor

ISIS issued a statement saying an Islamic State "fighter" carried out the attack. The ISIS claim comes via a statement released by the group's media wing, Amaq. The ISIS statement identified the attacker and called him "the Belgian." CNN has not confirmed the attacker's association with Belgium. Paris Prosecutor Francois Molins said he will reveal the shooter's identity on Friday at a news conference. data.title: ormer Florida State Prison warden Ron McAndrew and Former Arkansas death row chief Patrick Crain both went into their jobs supporting the death penalty. Both now oppose it.
data.description:
ormer Florida State Prison warden Ron McAndrew and Former Arkansas death row chief Patrick Crain both went into their jobs supporting the death penalty. Both now oppose it.

–– ADVERTISEMENT ––



Putting a prisoner to death “stays with you for a long time,” says Ron McAndrew.
The former warden of Florida State Prison told AFP his own mental health had begun to deteriorate by the time he left his position in 1998 after taking part in eight executions.
McAndrew is particularly concerned about the psychological wellbeing of the handful of officials who would be involved if Arkansas were to proceed with the rapid-fire executions.
“We wanted the governor (of Arkansas) to understand that he’s sitting in his office very comfortable. And these men are going to be partaking in a killing of another human being,” McAndrew told AFP.
McAndrew doesn’t use the word “execution”. He considers it a euphemism.
“These officers, they get to know these inmates,” he said.
“Twenty-four hours a day they work with these inmates. They feed them. They take them to get their showers, they take them for exercise. They stand in front of their cells and they talk to them when they feel lonely,” McAndrew said.
“Suddenly it’s the same officer who’s taking them to another room to kill them.”
“The experience is something that will stay with you for a long time; I don’t think it ever goes away.”

data.title: Injured Customer
data.description: A customer filled $25.05 of unleaded 91 fuel at pump 8 into their vehicle (Black, 4WD, Land Cruiser, ABZ - 473) and left the fuel nozzle inside their vehicle. When they drove away from fuel pump 8 the fuel nozzle was flung outside of the vehicle and made contact with another customer on the forecourt. This customer suffered a facial injury and became unconscious as a result.  The fuel nozzle was also damaged by being stretched too far and being flung that it is now unfit for use.
data.locationText: Caltex O'Connor, 309 Stock road, O'Connor, WA,  6163
data.unplannedEvent: The offending customer leaving the fuel nozzle inside their vehicle.
data.immediateActionTaken: Offending customer was requested to stop and leave their vehicle by my colleague while I called an ambulance and waited by the unconscious customer. The offending customer's details were then recorded and the medical staff was able to treat and then transport the injured individual.
